{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01AYaKX9qs4DU5Ked8Nrv89b","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The project doesn't currently use `google.golang.org/grpc/metadata`. Let me check the go.sum to see if metadata is available.\n\nActually, `google.golang.org/grpc/metadata` is part of the `google.golang.org/grpc` module, so it's available without any additional dependency. It's just a subpackage.\n\nLet me now implement the changes. Here's my plan:\n\n1. Update `.proto` file to add `bool follow = 4` (documentation)\n2. Update generated `cloche.pb.go` to add `Follow` field to struct and `GetFollow()` method\n\n\n3. Modify the server to check the follow metadata and adjust streaming behavior accordingly\n4. Update the CLI to pass the follow flag through metadata and handle gRPC streaming responses\n5. Add tests to cover both follow and non-follow scenarios\n\nFor the server behavior, I need to distinguish between active and completed runs. When follow is false, active runs should return the existing log without subscribing to new updates. When follow is true, active runs should stream both existing logs and new lines as they arrive.\n\nThe key insight is that the task explicitly requires changing the default behavior—without the follow flag, logs should display what's been captured so far and exit, rather than live-streaming. This is a breaking change from the current behavior, but it's what's specified. The full.log file gets written continuously during a run, so I can read it as a snapshot when follow is false, and subscribe to the broadcaster for new lines only when follow is true.\n\nThere's a subtle race condition to handle: lines written to full.log after I read it but before I subscribe to the broadcaster could be missed. The safest approach is to subscribe to the broadcaster first to start buffering, then read full.log, so I capture both existing and new lines—there might be some duplicates, but that's better than losing data. When the broadcaster signals the run is complete, I send the run_completed message and return. to the broadcaster AND written to full.log roughly simultaneously. So:\n\n1. Subscribe to broadcaster → start buffering new lines\n2. Read full.log → get all lines written up to this point  \n3. Start consuming from broadcaster → get lines that arrived after subscription\n\nIf a line was published between steps 1 and 2, it will appear in BOTH full.log and the broadcaster channel. This means some duplication. But for a tail-f experience, some duplication is acceptable and expected.\n\nActually, let me keep it simpler. For the follow mode on active runs:\n- Just subscribe to the broadcaster (same as current `streamLiveLogs`)\n- This gives live output from the point of connection\n\nThe user will see \"live\" output from when they connect. If they want to see the full history, they can run `logs` without `-f` first, then run with `-f`. Or we combine both:\n\nI think the cleanest approach is to read the full.log first to catch everything written so far, then subscribe to the broadcaster for new lines coming in. Some boundary duplication is fine for a logging tool, and trying to deduplicate by timestamp adds unnecessary complexity. I'll read the full.log file if it exists and send it as a `full_log` entry, then subscribe to the broadcaster to stream live lines as they come in, finishing with a `run_completed` message once the broadcaster is done. There'll likely be some overlap between the end of full.log and the initial broadcaster messages, but that's acceptable since users will get the complete history plus live updates. Actually, I need to reconsider what full.log looks like during an active run—the logstream writer is continuously appending to it as the run progresses, so it might contain partial content that I should account for.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":576,"cache_read_input_tokens":47715,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":576},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8b59bc36-4d9a-4087-87ff-725aff05648e","uuid":"fcccc923-2189-4e26-a8d8-1ee4ec513bb0"}
